<article>
    <h1>TIPS FOR GRO&#xAD;CERY SHOP&#xAD;PING AND STOR&#xAD;AGE</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201129/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-29"><time>2020-11-29</time></a>
        - <span>SINGAPORE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>• Check your re­frig­er­a­tor and pantry be­fore go­ing gro­cery shop­ping. This pre­vents du­pli­cate pur­chases.</p>
    <p>• Plan your pur­chases ahead. Make a shop­ping list and keep to it.</p>
    <p>• Avoid buy­ing a lot of per­ish­ables such as veg­eta­bles and fruit.</p>
    <p>• Buy­ing a larger size may seem more eco­nom­i­cal, but it is not so if you do not even­tu­ally use all of it.</p>
    <p>• Items on of­fer may be ex­pir­ing soon. Buy only if you will use them be­fore ex­piry.</p>
    <p>• Odd-look­ing, bruised or blem­ished fruit and veg­eta­bles can be trimmed and used for cook­ing.</p>
    <p>• Fol­low the stor­age in­struc­tions on the prod­uct’s pack­ag­ing.</p>
    <p>• Chips, crack­ers and ce­re­als last longer when kept in air­tight con­tain­ers.</p>
    <p>• Place prod­ucts that are nearer their ex­piry dates at the front of the re­frig­er­a­tor, freezer or cabi­net. This re­minds you to use them as soon as pos­si­ble.</p>

